{{Infobox Jewish leader | honorific-prefix = [[Rabbi]] | name = Avigdor Miller | honorific-suffix = | title = | image = | caption = | synagogue = Bais Yisroel of Rugby Torah Center | synagogueposition = Rabbi | yeshiva = [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]] | yeshivaposition = [[Mashgiach ruchani]] | organisation = | organisationposition = | began = | ended = | predecessor = | successor = | rabbi = | rebbe = | kohan = | hazzan = | rank = | other_post = <!---------- Personal details ----------> | birth_name = Victor Miller<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levine|first1=Yitzchok|title=Correspondence from a Gadol-in-the-Making|url=http://personal.stevens.edu/~llevine/jo_r_gifter.pdf|work=The Jewish Observer|issue=January/February 2006|page=48}}</ref> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1908|8|28}} | birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2001|4|20|1908|8|28}} | death_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States | yahrtzeit = 27 [[Nisan]] | buried = [[Mount of Olives]], [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]] | nationality = [[United States]] | denomination = [[Haredi Judaism]] | residence = | dynasty = | parents = | father = | mother = | spouse = Ettel | children = | occupation = | profession = | alma_mater = [[Yeshivas Knesses Yisrael (Slabodka)]] | semicha = [[Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary]] | signature = }} '''Avigdor HaKohen Miller''' (August 28, 1908 &ndash; April 20, 2001) was an American [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] [[rabbi]], author, and lecturer. He served simultaneously as a communal [[rabbi]], ''[[mashgiach ruchani]]'' of [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]], and as a [[teacher]] in [[Beis Yaakov]].
== Life and career == Avigdor Miller was born Victor Miller in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]. Miller was a [[kohen]]. Although he attended public school, only [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]] was spoken at home. After school, he went to learn in an afternoon [[Talmud Torah]]. When he finished his regular classes at the Talmud Torah, the school arranged for him to learn privately with Rav Avrohom Eliyahu Axelrod, a [[Lubavitcher]] [[Hasid]]. The Talmud Torah was unable to pay Axelrod, but he continued to teach Miller anyway. Miller would never forget that Axelrod continued to teach him without being paid, and spoke about him with appreciation.<ref name="Rav Avigdor Miller: The Later Years">[http://www.jewishpress.com/displayContent_new.cfm?contentid=16510&mode=a&contentname=Rav_Avigdor_Miller:_The_Later_Years&recnum=4&sectionid=14 Rav Avigdor Miller: The Later Years<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506135036/http://www.jewishpress.com/displayContent_new.cfm?contentid=16510&mode=a&contentname=Rav_Avigdor_Miller%3A_The_Later_Years&recnum=4&sectionid=14 |date=May 6, 2008 }}</ref> {{verify source|date=January 2017}}
=== Yeshiva University === At age 17, Miller went to [[New York City]] to attend [[Yeshiva University|Yeshiva College]]. He was elected student body president, and was also the ''[[Torah reading|baal korei]]''. He graduated from both YU and [[Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary|RIETS]], attaining a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and [[Semikha|rabbinical ordination]], respectively.
Rabbi [[Moshe Bick]], known as the ''Mezubizher Rav'', who arrived in the United States in 1927, was one of Rabbi Miller's early [[chavruta|study partners]].
While a student at [[Yeshiva University|YU]], Miller joined a ''[[chavurah]]'' together with five other young men (who were all to become notable [[Hareidi]] rabbis) to study [[Mussar literature|Mussar]] from the ''[[Sefer (Hebrew)|sefer]]'' ''[[Mesillas Yesharim]]''. The organizer of the ''chavurah'' was [[Yaakov Yosef Herman]], a builder of [[Orthodox Judaism]] in [[New York City]] of the early 20th-century. Herman encouraged Miller to travel to [[Europe]] to learn Torah in the [[yeshiva]]s there. Miller met Rabbi [[Isaac Sher]], the son-in-law of Rabbi [[Nosson Tzvi Finkel (Slabodka)|Nosson Tzvi Finkel]], who was in New York collecting funds for the [[Yeshivas Knesses Yisrael (Slabodka)|Slabodka yeshiva]] at the time. Sher did not raise much money, since this was during the [[Great Depression]]. But Sher would later declare this to be his most successful trip to America, since he was able to recruit and bring such a bright student to Slabodka.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}
=== Slabodke, Lithuania === In 1932, at the age of 24, Miller arrived in Europe to study at the Slabodka yeshiva in [[Vilijampole|Slabodke]], [[Lithuania]]. While there, he studied under Rabbi Sher. As a student in Slabodka, Miller was compelled to wear a coat during the summer, in order to conceal the multitude of overlapping patches that were his trousers.{{Citation needed|date=December 2007}}
Rabbi Shulman of Slabodka, a son-in-law of Sher, introduced Miller to Ettel Lessin, daughter of Rabbi [[Yaakov Moshe Lessin]] of Slabodka. They were married in 1935.
In the preface to all his books, and on many of his tapes, Miller stated that everything that is un-sourced should be considered the teachings of Rabbi Sher, whom he considered his primary rabbi.
=== Chelsea, Massachusetts === In 1938, due to the rise of [[Nazism]] and the tensions leading up to [[World War II]], Miller sought to return to the United States with his wife and two children. The American [[Consul (representative)|consul]] in [[Kaunas|Kovno]] at the time was a public high-school classmate and acquaintance of Miller's from Baltimore. He arranged passage for Miller's wife and children, who were not [[United States]] citizens.
Upon returning to the U.S., Miller became rabbi of [[Congregation Agudath Shalom]] in [[Chelsea, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levine|first1=Yitzchok|title=The Walnut Street Shul|url=http://personal.stevens.edu/~llevine/Walnut%20Street%20Shul.pdf|work=Hamodia Magazine|issue=8/20/2004|pages=10–11}}</ref> Initially, the community was taken aback by Miller's audacious pedagogy, and the sheer volume of his Torah presentations, attempting in vain to restrain his unconventional approach. Within a few years however, the community had changed their minds, desiring for Miller to stay longer.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
=== Brooklyn, New York === In 1944, Rabbi [[Yitzchok Hutner]], ''[[rosh yeshiva]]'' of [[Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin]], hired Miller to become its ''[[mashgiach ruchani]],'' in which position he served until 1964. In 1945, he also assumed the pulpit of the [[Young Israel]] of Rugby in [[East Flatbush, Brooklyn]]. In 1975, with neighborhood demographics changing, Miller established the Bais Yisroel of Rugby Torah Center on [[Ocean Parkway (Brooklyn)|Ocean Parkway]] in [[Midwood, Brooklyn]], which served as the main vehicle of his Torah dissemination until his death.
Miller also lectured at many yeshivas and [[Beis Yaakov]] schools throughout the years.
==Death and burial== Miller was taken to [[Maimonides Medical Center]] shortly after [[Passover]], 2001. Though his physical health was deteriorating, his mental acuity remained intact until his death on Friday morning, April 20, 2001.<ref>27 Nisan 5761</ref>
At a memorial service the following Sunday, Miller was eulogized by Rabbi Yosef Rosenblum, the ''rosh yeshiva'' of [[Beth Hamedrash Shaarei Yosher]]; Rabbi [[Shmuel Berenbaum]], ''rosh yeshiva'' of [[Mir yeshiva (Brooklyn)|Mir yeshiva]]; Rabbi [[Chaim Pinchas Scheinberg]], ''rosh yeshiva'' of ''[[Torah Ore]]'', who was in America on a visit from [[Jerusalem]]; and Miller's son-in-law, Rabbi Shmuel Brog.
Rabbi [[Simcha Bunim Cohen]], a grandson-in-law of Miller, noted that Miller's descendants married into the esteemed families of Torah scholars such as Rabbi [[Shmuel Ehrenfeld]], the [[Mattersburg|Mattersdorf]]er Rav (& Cohen's grandfather); Rabbi [[Reuven Grozovsky]]; Rabbi [[Aaron Kotler]] and Rabbi [[Baruch Sorotzkin]], ''rosh yeshiva'' of [[Telshe yeshiva|Telshe]].
Miller's body was transported to Israel, where a funeral was held at the [[Mir yeshiva (Jerusalem)|Mir Yeshiva]] in Jerusalem with a crowd of 25,000 people in attendance. He was eulogized by Rabbi [[Nosson Tzvi Finkel (Mir)|Noson Tzvi Finkel]] (the Mirrer rosh yeshiva), Rabbi [[Moishe Sternbuch]] and others. Rabbi [[Matisyohu Salomon]] was in Israel at the time, and he also delivered a moving eulogy.
Miller was buried on the [[Mount of Olives]] in ''chelkat Tashach''.
At a later event at the end of the [[Shiva (Judaism)|week of mourning]], Rabbi [[Yaakov Perlow]], the [[Novominsk (Hasidic dynasty)|Novominsk]]er [[Rebbe]], head of [[Agudath Israel of America|Agudath Israel]] and a pupil, remembered Rabbi Miller’s first days as ''mashgiach'' at Yeshiva Rabbi Chaim Berlin.
After his death, a synagogue, Nitei Avigdor ({{lang-he|נטעי אביגדור}}), was founded in Miller's name in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]], Brooklyn. The synagogue includes a library of Miller's tapes. The founder and rabbi of the synagogue is Rabbi Avrohom Shlomo Yabo, known as the Lemberger Rov, who also gives lectures based on Miller's teachings.
== Legacy == Miller was known within Orthodox Jewish circles as a master orator, having superb command of the [[English language]]. His personal magnetism drew students, young and old, from all Jewish backgrounds.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
Miller authored several books about [[Jewish history]], Jewish thought, [[Evolutionary Theory]], and other subjects.
Over a span of 50 years, more than 2,500 lectures by Miller in English were published as [[Compact Cassette|tape cassettes]], as well as several in Yiddish, of which several hundred thousand copies were sold. He gave most of his lectures in his Midwood synagogue. Topics covered are Torah education, ideology, and [[self-help]]. A range of ''[[sefer (Hebrew)|sefarim]]'' were compiled by his students from these lectures, called ''Q&A Thursday Nights With Rabbi Miller.''
Miller sought to awaken his audiences to the fundamental principle that there is a plan and purpose to every minute detail of life in this world, and he wished to make them happy and excited about its benefits.<ref>{{YouTube|gx_NgHIBRt4|Montage of him speaking about the Apple }}.</ref>
== Views == Miller was outspoken in his belief that the [[Holocaust]] was a divine response to Jewish cultural assimilation in Europe. He wrote: {{Cquote | Hitler was not only sent by Heaven, but was sent as a ''kindness'' from Heaven...Because assimilation and intermarriage are worse than death...and the German Jews and others ignored the Torah-teachers and refused to desist from their mad race into assimilation, the Nazis were sent to prevent them and rescue them before they were swallowed up by the nations.<ref>''Awake My Glory'' (Brooklyn, 1980), p. 146.</ref><ref>http://forward.com/articles/195467/a-visit-to-germany-reawakens-fears-of-an-ultra-ort/?p=3</ref>}}
Miller was a staunch opponent of [[Zionism]], in both its religious and secular forms, and was known to help the [[Satmar]] Hasidim translate their anti-Zionist ads in ''[[The New York Times]]''{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}. He was also a well-known opponent of the [[Theory of Evolution]].
Miller stated that the victims of the [[Kent State shootings]] were "bums and they deserved to be shot."<ref>https://torasavigdor.org/rav-avigdor-miller-on-july-4th-and-the-wicked-liberals/</ref>
Miller had sharp views about African-Americans and the apartheid in South Africa. Of President Lincoln he stated “... I hold it against him that he set free the blacks. Don’t think it’s being prejudiced, the blacks were doing wonderful. They were learning to be decent and civilized under their white masters.”<ref>{{Cite book|title=Q&A 2 Thursday Nights with Rabbi Avigdor Miller|last=Miller|first=Betzalel|publisher=Unknown|year=2011|isbn=|location=New York|pages=12}}</ref>
At his funeral in Jerusalem, his son said that he had instructed all his descendants to speak only Yiddish with their families.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
== Quotes == Miller has been noted for his ability to summarize ideas into easily digestible [[soundbite]]s. He once said, "Learning [[musar literature|Musar]] teaches one how to live, but learning ''[[Bava Kamma]] is'' living." <!-- * "[[Global warming]] is a concoction of the [[liberalism|liberal]]s; it is nothing to worry about." No context for this quote - Eliyak -->
