* {{IPA|/m, p, b/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], {{IPA|/p͡f/}} is bilabial-labiodental, whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=67}}
** {{IPA|/p͡f/}} occurs only in loanwords from Standard German.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}} Just as among many native German-speakers, it tends to be simplified to {{IPA|[f]}} word-initially. For example, ''Pflicht'' ('obligation') is pronounced {{IPA|[fliɕt]}}, or in careful speech {{IPA|[p͡fliɕt]}}.
** {{IPA|/v/}} is realized as {{IPAblink|w}} when it occurs after {{IPA|/k, t͡s, ʃ/}}, e.g. ''zwee'' {{IPA|[t͡sweː]}} ('two').{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=69}}
* {{IPA|/p, t, k/}} are voiceless fortis {{IPA|[{{IPA link|p}}, {{IPA link|t}}, {{IPA link|k}}]}}. They are [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] {{IPA|[pʰ, tʰ, kʰ]}} in most positions,{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=68}} but not when {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/ʃ/}} precedes in the same syllable, or when another plosive or affricate follows.
** If followed by a vowel, the fortis stops are [[syllabification|moved to the onset of the following syllable]] and voiced to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|b}}, {{IPA link|d}}, {{IPA link|ɡ}}]}}; see [[#Word-final obstruents|below]].{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}}
* {{IPA|/b, d, ɡ/}} are unaspirated lenis, more often voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPA link|p|b̥}}, {{IPA link|t|d̥}}, {{IPA link|k|ɡ̊}}]}} than voiced {{IPA|[{{IPA link|b}}, {{IPA link|d}}, {{IPA link|ɡ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=68}}{{fix|text=are the lenis affricates {{IPA|/d͡z, d͡ʒ/}} also voiceless?|date=June 2015}}
* {{IPA|/d͡z/}} as a phoneme appears only in a few words, such as ''spadséieren'' {{IPA|/ʃpɑˈd͡zɜɪ̯eʀen/}} ('to go for a walk'). {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} as a phoneme occurs only in loanwords from English.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}}
** Note that phonetic {{IPA|[d͡z]}} and {{IPA|[d͡ʒ]}} occur due to voicing of word-final {{IPA|/t͡s/}} and {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}}; see [[#Word-final obstruents|below]].
* {{IPA|/s/}} does not occur word-initially except in French and English loanwords. (In the oldest loans from French it is often replaced with {{IPA|/t͡s/}}.) {{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/z/}} only contrast between vowels.
* {{IPA|/ŋ, k, ɡ/}} are [[Velar consonant|velar]], {{IPA|/ʀ/}} is [[Uvular consonant|uvular]], whereas {{IPA|/j/}} is [[Palatal consonant|palatal]].{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=67}}
** The normal realization of {{IPA|/ʀ/}} is more often a [[Trill consonant|trill]] {{IPAblink|ʀ}} than a fricative {{IPAblink|ʁ}}. The fricative variant is used after short vowels before consonants. If the consonant is voiceless, the fricative is also voiceless, i.e. {{IPAblink|χ}}. Older speakers use the consonantal variant {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʀ}} ~ {{IPA link|ʁ}}]}} also in the word-final position, where younger speakers tend to vocalize the {{IPA|/ʀ/}} to a central vowel {{IPAblink|ə}} or {{IPAblink|ɐ}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=68}}
** {{IPA|/j/}} is frequently realized as {{IPAblink|ʒ}}, e.g. ''Juni'' {{IPA|[ˈjuːniː]}} or {{IPA|[ˈʒuːniː]}} ('June').{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=69}}
* {{IPA|/χ, ʁ/}} have two types of allophones: [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɕ}}, {{IPA link|ʑ}}]}} and uvular {{IPA|[χ, ʁ]}}. The latter occur after back vowels, whereas the former occur in all other positions.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=68}}
** The {{IPAblink|ʑ}} allophone appears only in a few words intervocalically, e.g. ''Spigel'' {{IPA|[ˈʃpiʑəl]}} ('mirror'), ''héijen'' {{IPA|[ˈhɜɪ̯ʑən]}} (inflected form of ''héich'' 'high'). Note that an increasing number of speakers do not distinguish between the alveolo-palatal allophones {{IPA|[ɕ, ʑ]}} and the postalveolar phonemes {{IPA|/ʃ, ʒ/}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|pp=68–69}}
* {{IPA|/l/}} is always "clear" {{IPAblink|l}}, never "dark" ([[velarized]]) *{{IPAblink|ɫ}}.

In external [[sandhi]], syllable-final {{IPA|/n/}} is deleted unless followed by {{IPA|[n t d t͡s h]}}, with few exceptions. Furthermore, some unusual consonant clusters may arise post-lexically after [[clitic]]isation of the [[definite article]] ''d''' (for feminine, neuter and plural forms), e.g. ''d'Land'' {{IPA|[dlɑnt]}} ('the country') or ''d'Kräiz'' {{IPA|[tkʀæːɪ̯t͡s]}} ('the cross').{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}} Due to cluster simplification this article often disappears entirely between consonants.

===Word-final obstruents===
Phonetically, word-final {{IPA|/b, d, d͡ʒ, ɡ, v, z, ʒ, ʁ/}} are realized exactly the same as {{IPA|/p, t, t͡ʃ, k, f, s, ʃ, χ/}}. In most cases, they are realized the same as the main allophones of {{IPA|/p, t, t͡ʃ, k, f, s, ʃ, χ/}} (i.e. voiceless), but when the next word begins with a vowel and is pronounced without a pause, they are realized the same as the main allophones of {{IPA|/b, d, d͡ʒ, ɡ, v, z, ʒ, ʁ/}}, i.e. voiced and are [[Syllabification|resyllabified]], that is, moved to the onset of the first syllable of the next word (the same happens with {{IPA|/ts/}}, which becomes {{IPA|[d͡z]}}, and the non-native affricate {{IPA|/p͡f/}}, which is also voiced to {{IPAblink|bv|b͡v}}). For instance, ''se'''ch''' eens'' (phonemically {{IPA|/zeχ ˈeːns/}}) is pronounced {{IPA|[zəˈʑeːns]}},{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|pp=68, 72}} although this article transcribes it {{IPA|[zəʑ‿ˈeːns]}} so that it corresponds more closely to the spelling. Similarly, ''eng interessant Iddi'' {{IPA|[eŋ intʀæˈsɑnd‿ˈidi]}} ('an interesting idea').

===Pronunciation of the letter ''g''===

In Luxembourgish, the letter ''g'' has no fewer than nine possible pronunciations, depending both on the origin of a word and the phonetic environment. Natively, it is pronounced {{IPA|[ɡ]}} initially and {{IPA|[ʁ ~ ʑ]}} elsewhere, the latter being devoiced to {{IPA|[χ ~ ɕ]}} at the end of a morpheme. Words from French, English and (in a few cases) German have introduced {{IPA|[ɡ]}} (devoiced {{IPA|[k]}}) in other environments, and [[French orthography]]'s [[Hard and soft G|"soft ''g''"]] indicates {{IPA|[ʒ]}} (devoiced {{IPA|[ʃ]}}).

By the now very common mergers of {{IPA|[ʒ]}} and {{IPA|[ʑ]}}, as well as {{IPA|[ʃ]}} and {{IPA|[ɕ]}}, this number may be reduced to seven, however. The pronunciation {{IPA|[j]}} is also (generally) not obligatory but a common alternative to {{IPA|[ʑ]}} in the environment indicated below.

