* The nasal vowels appear only in loanwords from French, whereas the oral front rounded vowels appear in loans from both French and German.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}}
* {{IPA|/i, iː, u, uː, o/}} are close to the corresponding cardinal vowels {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|o}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
** Some speakers may realize {{IPA|/o/}} as open-mid {{IPAblink|ɔ}}, especially before {{IPA|/ʀ/}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
* {{IPA|/e/}} has two allophones:
** Before velars: close-mid {{IPAblink|e}}, which for some speakers may be open-mid {{IPAblink|ɛ}} – this is especially frequent before {{IPA|/ʀ/}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
** All other positions: mid central vowel with variable rounding, but more often slightly rounded {{IPAblink|ə̹}} than unrounded {{IPAblink|ə̜}}. Contrary to Standard German, the sequence of {{IPA|[ə]}} and a sonorant never results in a syllabic sonorant; however, Standard German spoken in Luxembourg often also lacks syllabic sonorants, so that e.g. ''tragen'' is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈtʀaːɡən]}}, rather than {{IPA|[ˈtʀaːɡn̩]}} or {{IPA|[ˈtʀaːɡŋ̍]}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|pp=70–71}}{{sfnp|Dudenredaktion|Kleiner|Knöbl|2015|p=39}}
* {{IPA|/eː, oː/}} are higher than close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e̝ː}}, {{IPA link|o̝ː}}]}} and may be even as high as {{IPA|/i, u/}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
** Before {{IPA|/ʀ/}}, {{IPA|/eː/}} is realized as open-mid {{IPAblink|ɛː}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
* The quality of {{IPA|/æ/}} matches the prototypical IPA value of the {{angle bracket|{{IPA|æ}}}} symbol ({{IPAblink|æ}}).{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
* {{IPA|/ɐ/}} appears only in unstressed syllables. Phonetically it is a near-open near-back unrounded vowel {{IPAblink|ɐ|ɐ̠}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}} It is similar to {{IPA|/ɑ/}}, though it is shorter and somewhat more central. Phonemically, it can be analyzed either as a marginal phoneme or a non-prevocalic sequence of {{IPA|/e/}} and {{IPA|/ʀ/}}.
* {{IPA|/ɑ/}} is near-open {{IPAblink|ɑ|ɑ̝}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=70}}
* {{IPA|/aː/}}, a phonological back vowel (the long counterpart of {{IPA|/ɑ/}}), is phonetically near-front {{IPAblink|a|a̠ː}}. Sometimes, it may be as front and as high as {{IPA|/æ/}} ({{IPAblink|æː}}), though without losing its length.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|pp=68, 70–71}}

===Diphthongs===
[[File:Luxembourgish diphthong chart - part 1.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Part 1 of native [[diphthong]]s of Luxembourgish, from {{Harvcoltxt|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}]]
[[File:Luxembourgish diphthong chart - part 2.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Part 2 of native diphthongs of Luxembourgish, from {{Harvcoltxt|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}]]

{|  class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
|+ Diphthong phonemes{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
|-
! Closing
| {{IPA|ɜɪ̯ əʊ̯ æːɪ̯ æːʊ̯ ɑɪ̯ ɑʊ̯}}
|-
! Centering
| {{IPA|iə̯ uə̯}}
|-
! Non-native
| {{IPA|oɪ̯}}
|}

* The ending points of the closing diphthongs tend to be fairly close, more like {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}} than {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
* The starting points of {{IPA|/ɜɪ̯, əʊ̯/}} are typically schwa-like {{IPAblink|ə}}, but the first element of {{IPA|/ɜɪ̯/}} may be more of a centralized front vowel {{IPAblink|e̞|ë̞}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
* The starting points of {{IPA|/æːɪ̯, æːʊ̯/}}, {{IPA|/ɑɪ̯, ɑʊ̯/}} as well as {{IPA|/iə̯/}} and {{IPA|/uə̯/}} are similar to the corresponding short monophthongs {{IPA|[{{IPA link|æ}}, {{IPA link|ɑ}}, {{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
** The first elements of {{IPA|/æːɪ̯, æːʊ̯/}} may be phonetically short {{IPA|[æ]}} in fast speech or in unstressed syllables.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
* The centering diphthongs end in the mid central unrounded area {{IPAblink|ə}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}}
* {{IPA|/oɪ̯/}} appears only in loanwords from Standard German.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}}

The {{IPA|/æːɪ̯ – ɑɪ̯/}} and {{IPA|/æːʊ̯ – ɑʊ̯/}} contrasts arose from a former lexical tone contrast: the shorter {{IPA|/ɑɪ̯, ɑʊ̯/}} were used in words with Accent 1, whereas the lengthened {{IPA|/æːɪ̯, æːʊ̯/}} were used in words with Accent 2 (see [[Pitch-accent language#Franconian dialects]].){{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=72}}

Additional phonetic diphthongs arise after vocalisation of {{IPA|/ʀ/}}.{{sfnp|Gilles|Trouvain|2013|p=71}} These are {{IPA|[iːə̯, uːə̯, oːə̯, ɛːə̯]}}, with {{IPA|[iːɐ̯, uːɐ̯, oːɐ̯, ɛːɐ̯]}} as possible alternatives. However, the sequence {{IPA|/aːʀ/}} is realized the same as long {{IPA|/aː/}}, unless a vowel follows within the same word.

In loanwords from Standard German (such as ''[[Bad Dürkheim|Bad D'''ür'''kheim]]'' and ''[[Föhr|F'''öhr''']]'') {{IPA|[yːə̯]}} and {{IPA|[øːə̯]}} also occur, again with {{IPA|[yːɐ̯]}} and {{IPA|[øːɐ̯]}} as possible alternatives.

