'''Speech shadowing''' is an experimental technique in which subjects [[speech repetition|repeat speech]] immediately after hearing it (usually through [[earphones]]). The [[reaction time]] between hearing a word and [[pronunciation|pronouncing]] it can be as short as 254 ms<ref name="Marslen">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/244522a0 | last1 = Marslen-Wilson | first1 = W. | title = Linguistic structure and speech shadowing at very short latencies | journal = Nature | volume = 244 | issue = 5417 | pages = 522–523 | year = 1973 | pmid = 4621131 }}</ref> or even 150 ms.<ref name="Chistovich">{{Cite journal | last1 = Marslen-Wilson | first1 = W. D. | doi = 10.1016/0167-6393(85)90036-6 | title = Speech shadowing and speech comprehension | journal = Speech Communication | volume = 4 | pages = 55–73| year = 1985 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> This is only the delay duration of a speech [[syllable]]. While a person is only asked to repeat words, they also automatically process their [[syntax]] and [[semantics]].<ref name="Marslen"/> Words repeated during the practice of shadowing imitate the parlance of the overheard words more than the same words read aloud by that subject.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.3758/BF03194890 | last1 = Shockley | first1 = K. | last2 = Sabadini | first2 = L. | last3 = Fowler | first3 = C. A. | title = Imitation in shadowing words | journal = Perception & Psychophysics | volume = 66 | issue = 3 | pages = 422–429 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15283067 }} [http://app.psychonomic-journals.org/content/66/3/422.full.pdf PDF]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The technique is also used in [[language learning]].
[[Functional imaging]] finds that the shadowing of [[nonword]]s<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Peschke | first1 = C. | last2 = Ziegler | first2 = W. | last3 = Kappes | first3 = J. | last4 = Baumgaertner | first4 = A. | title = Auditory–motor integration during fast repetition: The neuronal correlates of shadowing | doi = 10.1016/j.neuroimage.2009.03.061 | journal = NeuroImage | volume = 47 | issue = 1 | pages = 392–402 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19345269 | pmc = }}</ref> occurs through the dorsal stream that links auditory and motor representations of speech through a pathway that starts in the [[superior temporal gyrus|superior temporal cortex]], goes to the [[inferior parietal lobule|inferior parietal cortex]] and then the [[inferior frontal gyrus|posterior inferior frontal cortex]] ([[Broca's area]]).<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hickok | first1 = G. | last2 = Poeppel | first2 = D. | doi = 10.1016/j.cognition.2003.10.011 | title = Dorsal and ventral streams: A framework for understanding aspects of the functional anatomy of language | journal = Cognition | volume = 92 | issue = 1–2 | pages = 67–99 | year = 2004 | pmid = 15037127 | pmc = }}</ref>
Speech shadowing was first used as a research technique by the Leningrad Group led by [[Ludmilla A.Chistovich]] in the late 1950s.<ref name="Chistovich"/><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Chistovich | first1 = L. A. | last2 = Pickett | first2 = J. M. | last3 = Porter | first3 = R. J. | title = Speech research at the I. P. Pavlov Institute in Leningrad/St. Petersburg | doi = 10.1121/1.422540 | journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 103 | issue = 5 | page = 3024| year = 1998 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> It has been used in research into [[speech perception]]<ref name= "Marslen"/> and [[stuttering]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1121/1.398742 | last1 = Harbison Jr | first1 = D. C. | last2 = Porter Jr | first2 = R. J. | last3 = Tobey | first3 = E. A. | title = Shadowed and simple reaction times in stutterers and nonstutterers | journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 86 | issue = 4 | pages = 1277–1284 | year = 1989 | pmid = 2808903 }}</ref>
==Experimental applications== The speech shadowing technique is used in [[dichotic listening tests]]. The first one to apply this technique was E. Colin Cherry in 1953.{{sfn|Cherry|1953|p=976}} During dichotic listening tests, subjects are presented with two different messages, one in their right ear and one in their left. The participants are often asked to focus on only one of the different messages and this is where the speech shadowing technique is used. Participants are instructed to shadow the attended message by repeating it out loud with a delay of a few seconds between hearing a word and repeating the word. The speech shadowing technique is significant for these experiments because it ensures that the subjects are attending to the desired message.<ref>Goldstein, B. (2011). ''Cognitive Psychology: Connecting Mind, Research, and Everyday Experience--with coglab manual. (3rd ed.).'' Belmont, CA: Wadsworth.</ref> Various other stimuli are then presented to the other ear, and subjects are afterwards queried on what they can recall from the other message.{{sfn|Cherry|1953|p=977-979}}
